Reasoning: The paper describes techniques to improve the running time of machine learning algorithms when data is sparse. This suggests that the paper belongs to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions several models that can be constructed using these techniques, including decision trees, decision graphs, Bayesian networks, and naive-Bayes clustering models, which are commonly studied in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the E-step of the EM algorithm, which is a common technique used in data science (cs.DS) and computational linguistics (cs.CL). Finally, the paper discusses the extraction of counts from discrete data, which is a common task in database systems (cs.DB).
